<h1 class="display-4 text-center mt-3 mb-4">An Introduction to Pathfinding</h1>

<div id="assembly" class="container text-justify pb-3">

    <div class="assemdesc mt-3">
        I created these Pathfinding Lectures for game designers and computer scientists with an interest in understanding the underlying mechanics of graph traversal and search.
        It may be helpful to students taking a Graph Theory course, or otherwise those similarly interested in discrete structures.

        <br /><br />

        In this tutorial and code, you will learn the following algorithms and their implementations
        <ul class="list p-3">
            <li>Breadth-First Search</li>
            <li>Depth-First Search</li>
            <li>Dijkstra's Algorithm (uniform-cost search)</li>
            <li>Greed best-first Search</li>
            <li>A* Search</li>
        </ul>

        To motivate the learner, several demo applications are provided.
        <ul class="list p-3">
            <li>Stack vs Queue Demonstration</li>
            <li>Graph construction, unweighted pathfinding, and backtracking</li>
            <li>Weighted Graph construction and finding the minimum path with Dijkstra's algorithm</li>
            <li>Mazes and pathfinding - DFS vs. Dijkstra vs. A*</li>
            <li>Implementation of the 8-puzzle and solving using A* or greedy best-first.</li>
        </ul>

        Additionally, I have created a <a asp-controller="Portfolio" asp-action="FifteenPuzzle> 15-Puzzle solver</a> using Machine Learning and A*, which builds on the work presented here.

        I have used these lectures to successfully teach a motivated high-school student to obtain an operative understanding of the material, but I would consider this to be college-level.

        <br /><br />
        The accompanying code can be found in this <a target="_blank" href="https://github.com/RyanTonerCode/Pathfinding-Tutorial" rel="noreferrer">GitHub Repository</a>.
    </div>

</div>

